ost </i>and the<i> Los Angeles Times </i>to forgo the decades-long traditio=
n of endorsing a presidential candidate. In each case, I=E2=80=99m told, th=
e decision was made by the respective billionaire owners of the newspapers,=
 <b>Jeff Bezos </b>and <b>Patrick Soon-Shiong</b>, which has led to broad
suspicion that they were preemptively capitulating to Trump in order to pro=
tect their own personal or business interests=E2=80=94or neutering their ed=
itorial boards in order to position their companies to advertisers and audi=
ences as at least <i>vaguely</i> centrist. Bezos=E2=80=99s Amazon has highl=
y lucrative government contracts, after all, and, in a stroke of particular=
ly bad timing, Trump met with executives from Bezos=E2=80=99s aerospace com=
pany, Blue Origin, on Friday. Soon-Shiong once sought an appointment as Tru=
mp=E2=80=99s healthcare czar and has other business interests pending feder=
al regulatory review. <br/><br/>At the <i>Post</i>, C.E.O. <b>Will Lewis </=
b>framed the endorsement decision as a return to the paper=E2=80=99s roots,=
 noting that prior to the 1976 <b>Gerald</b> <b>Ford</b>-<b>Jimmy</b> <b>Ca=
rter</b> election, the paper did not regularly endorse candidates. This rat=
ionale left many <i>Post </i>journalists, already pissed after a summer of =
discontent, feeling gaslit and irate,
especially given that the paper=E2=80=99s editorial board had already draft=
ed an endorsement of Harris. It also reignited their latent anxieties about=
 Lewis=E2=80=99s moral compass dating back to the scrutiny over his role in=
 the <b>Murdoch</b> phone-hacking scandal. (Bezos is not commenting on the =
decision.) Meanwhile, the <i>LA</i> <i>Times</i>, which had also been prepa=
red to endorse Harris, offered no explanation for its decision, though Soon=
-Shiong made a feeble attempt to blame his own editorial board for not draf=
ting a factual analysis of the candidates=E2=80=99 respective policies. <br=
/><br/>In any event, the decisions led to <i>thousands</i> of subscriber ca=
ncellations at both papers, caused a furor in the newsrooms, and even inspi=
red high-level resignations. <i>Post </i>editor-at-large <b>Robert Kagan</b=
>, the author of a 2023 editorial warning about an inevitable Trump dictato=
rship, resigned in protest, as did <i>LA</i> <i>Times </i>editorial editor =
<b>Mariel Garza</b>, who said
the decision to forgo an endorsement made her paper look =E2=80=9Ccraven an=
d hypocritical.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Meanwhile, eight of the <i>Post</i>=E2=
=80=99s editorial columnists described their paper=E2=80=99s decision as an=
 =E2=80=9Cabandonment of the fundamental editorial convictions of the newsp=
aper.=E2=80=9D The paper=E2=80=99s storied former executive editor <b>Marty=
 Baron </b>accused his alma mater, in turgid prose, of =E2=80=9Ccowardice, =
with democracy as its casualty,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdisturbing spinelessn=
ess at an institution famed for courage.=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
