          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Based on the most r=
ecent ratings, the audience for Cooper and Charlamagne=E2=80=99s contretemp=
s was almost certainly between 600,000 and 700,000 total viewers, a populat=
ion roughly equivalent to the District of Columbia itself, though certainly=
 far older (only one-fifth of Cooper=E2=80=99s audience is below the age of=
 55). If it was any higher, that was probably due to Charlamagne, whose inf=
luence today is so significant that both CNN and MSNBC recently decided to =
preempt their own programs in order to simulcast <i>his </i>podcast intervi=
ew with Harris. Regardless of CNN=E2=80=99s ambitions to prioritize its dig=
ital business, the fact that its average primetime audience right now is ar=
ound half a million people, despite the fact that we are just <i>days </i>a=
way from the aforementioned historic and highly consequential election, is =
a <i>much</i> more profound story
of our time than two aborted editorials.<br/><br/>Meanwhile, after years of=
 hemorrhaging subscribers and revenue, <i>The Washington Post</i> has added=
 just 4,000 net new subscribers <i>in an election year</i>, which is peanut=
s for a media company of that scale. To paraphrase Lewis=E2=80=99s own inde=
licate diagnosis of his paper=E2=80=99s problems, people are not reading th=
eir stuff. Of course, the<i> Los Angeles Times </i>is in even worse shape, =
with a mere 500,000 digital subscribers. Of course, <i>both </i>papers now =
have even <i>fewer</i> subscribers, since at least 1,600 and at least 2,000=
 have reportedly canceled their <i><u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/=
c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTeG5fQkNfTDFhNnZLaUI0TTFYND0iL=
CJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9kYXZpZGZvbGtlbmZsaWsvc3RhdHVzLzE4NDk5NDIxMjIx=
MDQ4NTI4NDc_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPUluK1RoZStSb29tKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTAlMkY=
yNSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pbyIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNj=
A2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MTk1MzI2OH0/10e7c3b610c9449e6be37704ef43b=
b5548a2a3b118037bab9c3cd54ed20ebef9" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration=
:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">Post</a></u></i> and <i><u><a href=3D=
"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTeG=
5fQkNfTDFhNnZLaUI0TTFYND0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZ3VhcmRpYW4uY29tL=
3VzLW5ld3MvMjAyNC9vY3QvMjUvbG9zLWFuZ2VsZXMtdGltZXMtb3duZXItYmxvY2tzLWhhcnJp=
cy1lbmRvcnNlbWVudD91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249SW4rVGhlK1Jvb20rLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg=
xMCUyRjI1JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOi=
JmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoxOTUzMjY5fQ/8d382354b6872f4d14bfe3=
1fd7c68331603d32853d807093a359c691e1fa93f8" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-dec=
oration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">LA Times</a></u></i> subscript=
ions, respectively. These are tolerable losses, of course, but they highlig=
ht the diminutive nature of their audiences in the first place. <br/><br/><=
i>The</i> <i>New York</i> <i>Times</i>, by contrast, is seen as the great s=
uccess story of the media industry, given its transformation into a multifa=
ceted news <i>and </i>lifestyle <i>and </i>games <i>and </i>recipes platfor=
m, as well as its ability to keep breaking news at an impressive clip. But,=
 in the era of hyper-fragmentation, even the nation=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cpape=
r of record=E2=80=9D is really just the paper of record for the well-educat=
ed, mostly liberal elite who are
overwhelmingly inclined to vote against Trump=E2=80=94which explains in par=
t why both <b>Biden </b>and Harris decided to forgo the customary sit-down =
with the paper=E2=80=99s editorial board, much to the consternation of <b>A=
=2EG. Sulzberger</b>. <br/><br/>Obvious=
ly, the broad polarization of American=
 politics, and certainly Trump=E2=80=99s own demonization of the media, pla=
ys a significant role in all of this. At the same time, the media itself be=
ars some responsibility for becoming so insular and self-obsessed that it m=
issed the memo on its own waning influence, and how little the latest <i>At=
lantic </i>cover or the rantings of <b>Joe </b>and <b>Mika</b>=E2=80=94or, =
yes, a newspaper=E2=80=99s endorsement=E2=80=94matter to an electorate busy=
 listening to <b>Joe Rogan </b><i>or</i> <b>Alex Cooper </b><i>or</i> Charl=
amagne, or scrolling through TikTok or Instagram, or, more to the point, no=
t paying attention <i>at all</i>. <br/><br/>Forget whether the <i>Post </i>=
and the <i>LA Times</i> made appropriate or
shameful decisions here, the reality is that neither successfully innovated=
 to the point where such a decision might have actually mattered. =E2=80=9C=
This self-righteous, self-obsessed, self-important B.S. is what=E2=80=99s k=
illing the very institutions these people claim to be fighting to protect,=
=E2=80=9D one top media executive told me Friday. =E2=80=9CTheir buildings =
are burning down and they=E2=80=99re pissing into the fire, warning America=
 will melt if it can=E2=80=99t learn about a lame newspaper endorsement.=E2=
=80=9D<br/><br/>On Friday, while discussing the <i>Washington Post </i>and =
<i>Los Angeles Times</i>=E2=80=99 decisions to forgo an endorsement, a coll=
eague proffered that this was =E2=80=9Cthe downside of billionaires saving =
newspapers.=E2=80=9D Perhaps, but the <i>real </i>downside was that they ne=
ver actually saved the institutions in the first place.<br/></td>
